bug.short_desc: Extend RSE to support management of WinCE devices

long_desc.thetext:
RSE can be extended to support remote management of WinCE devices using the Remote APIs provided by Microsoft. RAPI will allow doing all kinds of file operations from the RSE and maybe some other things like launch actions. WinCE (eRCP) developers will be able to deploy applications faster and will have a fully integrated development environment.
I have some experience with WinCE devices and I am planning to contribute to the TM project for implementing this enhancement.

As Martin has already said in the newsgroup thread one important thing is to decide how WinCE devices should be represented in the RSE framework. I think we should define a system type similar to the Local one. We can manage only the device connected to the local PC and it doesn't make sense to use hostnames. When RAPI is initialized one could use the APIs as he is operating with local resources. One important difference is that WinCE connections should support Connect/Disconnect actions corresponding to initializing/uninitializing the underlying communication layers.

OK, time for update :) it turns out that RAPI is replaced with RAPI2 which has almost the same functionality with two major enhancements: - support for multiple applications working with the device at the same time - support for multiple remote devices as well as the ability to query for information about each of them
Microsoft strongly recommends using the new RAPI2, so I decided to use it instead of the old RAPI. I think that ActiveSync 4.1 is the first version which supports RAPI2 (the current one is 4.5), so the old versions of ActiveSync won't be supported which is not a big problem in my opinion.
A little bit about the new RAPI2 design - the all functionality is exposed with five COM interfaces (copied from MSDN): IRAPIDesktop - The connection point container for all devices IRAPIDevice - Represents a connected remote device IRAPIEnumDevices - Enumerates over all connected devices IRAPISession - Provides methods that replace the Remote API (RAPI) functions IRAPISink - Implemented by client application to receive connection events
I have decided to implement a thin Java wrapper for each interface and to use these wrappers for implementing my RSE plug-ins. This design has two major advantages: the native code is very simple and easy to debug; you can work with the whole set of APIs in Java. I have ported parts of IRAPIDesktop, IRAPIDevice, IRAPIEnumDevices and IRAPISession which will enable implementing a file subsystem for WinCE. You can find attached jrapi.zip which includes all my sources so far. I have ported some of the examples from the WindowsMobile SDK in Java as proof-of-concept (com.prosyst.wince.examples.RapiExamples). If you don't have a WinCE device you can still run the examples using a stanadalone emulator images which can be downloaded from [1]. Of course you will need to install ActiveSync [2] as well.
Any comments about the design and implementation of these wrappers are very welcome! The next step will be implementing a file subsystem for WinCE using these interfaces. I will let you know when I have something.
[1] http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=C62D54A5-183A-4A1E-A7E2-CC500ED1F19A&displaylang=en [2] http://www.microsoft.com/windowsmobile/activesync/default.mspx

Thanks a lot for your contribution! This can potentially bring Eclipse a big step forward. Here are some initial comments and questions:
* The structure of your ZIP archive looks like an Eclipse project, but there is no .project file. If you are managing your code from Eclipse, please add any administrative files (.project, .classpath, .settings) to make it easier for adopters to browse the code, and eventually add it to our Repository.
* Your Copyright headers indicate yourself as the Copyright owner, but your E-Mail includes prosyst. Are you contributing this work as part of your private spare time, or as a Prosyst employee? Do you have the right (from your employer) to contribute under the EPL? The question is, who is really the copyright owner. Most companies are set up such that any software created during work time is owned by the company, and not the individual.
* build.xml does not have a copyright header, please add one.
There is more information about the legal / copyright things to consider in http://wiki.eclipse.org/TM_and_RSE_FAQ#How_do_I_submit_a_contribution_beyond_a_simple_bug_fix.3F
As a confirmation that you're understanding this, please add a comment like the following on this bugzilla item. In case you actually referenced non-EPL material, please let me know and we can go through it offline:
Legal Message: I, {name}, declare that I developed attached code from scratch, without referencing any 3rd party materials except material licensed under the EPL. {I am authorized by my employer to make this contribution under the EPL.}

I like the idea of separating the thin RAPI Java wrapper from the RSE implementation.
For the examples that you ported, the original Copyright from Microsoft might still apply. For now, please add a comment in RapiExamples.java that indicates where the original code was taken from, and under what license Microsoft distributes that code.
For the interfaces, I do not expect such problems since interfaces and APIs are inherently not copyrightable (because their whole intent is to be publicly available). Still, if you find a link to the Copyright notice under which Microsoft distributes the relevant headers, that might be helpful down the road.
On the Microsoft link you added about ActiveSync, it says that matters are different on Vista (There is a mobile device center). Does that mean that your dll is not compatible with Vista?
Finally, some unit tests (that potentially run against the emulator) would be great.
Thanks!

I have attached an updated version of my code for review. The changes are:
- RapiSession#removeDirectory() is added, I have forgotten to implement this method in the previous version - The signatures of IRapiSesison#readFile and IRapiSession#writeFile are changed - Unit tests are added. An ActiveSync connection with either device or emulator should be established before running them. - Project files added (.classpath, .project)
There is no javadoc for most of the APIs because they are still not final. If you have any suggestions for changes, I will be happy to discuss them.

There is an interesting usecase for using RAPI2 which eRCP could benefit from. CeRapiInvoke allows calling DLL routines on the device from a desktop application which could be used for implementing "remote eSWT", i.e. running an eRCP/eSWT application on a PC and rendering its GUI on the device (think of the linux X server ;) This will enable running/debugging applications directly on device/emulator from Eclipse.

The first version of the WinCE file subsystem is available! All types of file operations are supported and I am very satisfied with the achieved results. The ability to "directly" edit files on the device is super cool, I have been always wanting to do that. Of course there is still a lot of work to be done (see the known issues) but I think this is enough for initial version.
The attached file contains both updated version of the RAPI2 wrappers and initial version of the WinCE file subsystem provided as two PDE projects. The file subsystem requires TM 3.0M5 because of some API changes that I've requested (bug #219098). I decided to export the RAPI2 functionality using the standard OSGi mechanism - the Export-Package manifest header. The other changes related to the RAPI2 stuff are: - javadoc added to all public APIs - minor API changes - OS#CoInitialize replaced with OS#CoInitializeEx in order to be able to initialize the COM library in MTA
Known issues and limitations for the current state of the WinCE file subsystem: - the default New Connection dialog is confusing because it prompts for a hostname which is not used in any way. RAPI2 provides information about each connected device such as unique ID, name, etc., so the correct behaviour of the this dialog should be to display a combo with all found devices and to prompt the user to select one. Strangely, the latest version of ActiveSync doesn't support connecting multiple devices, so the current implementation of my ConnectorService is to always connect to the first found device. I suppose that WDMC on Vista does support multiple devices and I will consider implementing custom New Connection dialog for the next version. However this may require some API changes in the IHost which is a topic of another discussion - the error handling is very poor at this moment, the user will see strange error codes returned by RAPI2 instead of meaningful error messages (P1 for the next version) - the progress monitors are not used and there is no way to cancel a long-time operation (P1 for the next version) - unable to receive connect/disconnect notifications leading to bad user experience. Wrapper for IRAPISink is required to receive these notifications (P2 for the next version) - setLastModified() and setReadOnly() are not implemented, should be added in the IRapiSession as well - there are no unit tests for now; I have to investigate the unit test framework used by RSE and integrate with it
The TODO list includes: - implementing launch actions with IRAPISession#CeRapiInvoke - implementing processes subsystem; this may require installing an additional dll on the remote device but it will be a *very* powerful feature because the default task manager is very limited
DISCLAIMER: I take no responsibility if you loose some important data using this code. It is still a work in progress so it is (very) possible to contain bugs. Please use an emulator for testing purposes.

Something I have missed in the known issues which is very important: - there is no EFS support for now, so you can't create remote projects/folders; this issue is with highest priority for the next version. I will contribute a developer doc about what an extender must do to support EFS as well.
On a completely different note, Martin and others -- do you think it is a good idea to attach the compiled plug-ins here? I would like to get some feedback from the community and I don't want to push them to compile the stuff.

Contribution looks great, though I have a few requests:
* Would you mind refactoring into an org.eclipse namespace right away? I'd suggest following project / plugin names: --> org.eclipse.rse.subsystems.wince --> org.eclipse.tm.rapi --> org.eclipse.tm.rapi.examples --> org.eclipse.tm.rapi.tests
* Bundle-Vendor will become Eclipse.org but we can do this after contribution is approved by Eclipse Legal Review
* build.properties and plugin.properties should also carry a Copyright Header
* the DLL should be in folder lib/os/win32/x86 because we might want an x86_64 variant of it for win64 eventually. Somehow I think OSGi is capable of automatically adding a PATH to such directories such that you even don't need to specify it on the System.loadLibrary() line... but I'm not 100% sure
* Why is com.prosyst.rse.wince.Activator public API? I'd propose making it "internal". Same for subsystems.files.wince ... or why did you think you'd want these to be public API? Public API just means that you'd need to maintain API compatibility so you're limited in what you can do. Making something API should be well thought out.
* Please don't access SystemFileResources -- it's internal non-API. Better Copy the Strings or work with us to come up with shareable public API Strings
* Messages.java is missing a Copyright header
* If there's any files where you referenced existing java files in order to create them by means of copy-and-modify, please reference the original Copyright Header to give original authors credit. I'm not sure but it could be that IWinCESubSystem is originally Copyright by IBM - the class comment looks pretty familiar to me. Remember that even though we're allowed to copy stuff under the EPL, we still need to maintain original Copyright licenses because the original authors remain the owners of that code -- it's just licensed to us. So we should keep track of the history of code that we copy.
Thanks again for this great contribution. I can't wait passing it on to Eclipse EMO Legal Review. You don't need to work on all my points for making that happen - but it would be good to get it refactored into an Eclipse.org namespace, and add the missing Copyright headers.
Thanks!

I believe that there is still a bit more cleanup to do, but this can be done once the code is committed to Eclipse CVS. Alternatively, you can also continue working on the code and we commit your changes as a patch later on. Such cleanup includes for instance:
* Those files where you credit IBM or Wind River as original authors in the copyright header should have a different "Contributors" section: currently these claim you were original API and Implementation provider but this is not true. It should say e.g.
Contributors: Radoslav Gerganov (ProSyst) - derived from DStoreConnectorServiceManager
* .classpath files should reference the J2SE-1.4 container
* Require-Bundle is preferred over Import-Package since it can carry version number constraints
* internal.services.wince.files/Messages.java uses the old-style Messages mechanism, it should better use NLS (or be merged with the other Messages class)
* Export-Package in MANIFEST should always export "internal" packages as well but with an ;x-internal=true -- use PDE-Tools/Cleanup Manifest wizard to do this automagically
* For the native DLL that you checked in, I'd like to see a README.txt somewhere listing the environment you used for compiling (e.g. Windows XP SP2 with Visual Studio Express 2007 and Platform SDK Version xyz)

Actually, I do not think there's a need for user docs for tm.rapi since this is a library that users will never directly deal with. What I had in mind was user docs for rse.subsystems.wince, which could e.g. explain how to set up a WinCE emulator, any specifics of the new connection wizard for WinCE, any specifics of the file system access.
But I think there's currently so little to say that it's not yet worthwile doing a user doc.
Regarding Developer Docs (including Javadoc) it's different: these should be done for tm.rapi but not necessarily for rse.subsystems.wince since the latter has almost no API.
That brings me to another important question: Usually I'm reluctant releasing a new component like tm.rapi as 1.0 right away without much community review of the APIs. Note that with a 1.0 release we sort of promise to the community that we'll try very hard to maintain backward compatibility in the future.
On the other hand, given that JRapi is a very thin layer on top of MS RAPI2 there is probably not much area of freedom with respect to defining the API anyways, and it might be OK starting with 1.0 after all.
What's your personal impression Radoslav? Do you feel that the JRAPI is as good as it can possibly get and we should go ahead with 1.0 -- or should we better start with an "Incubation" version like 0.1 which gives us the freedom to change API in the next iteration without being backward compatible? Note that we can always easily rev up version numbers, but we can never rev them down.

So I am inclined to start with version 0.1 and gather community feedback.
